        <span id="ChapterQuoteAudio">
        “I began to scream and as we neared the house, my sister heard and she ran outside to help me.” 
        </span>
        <div id="ChapterText" class="clearfix">
            <!--span id="ChapterByline">
            <span id="textspanlichapter22">ELLIS LI</span><br /><span id="textspanlichapter24">DAUGHTER</span>
            </span-->

            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText"></span>
                When my sister Melba married Harold Hersley, they moved out onto a farm in the Roberts area. They had a team of horses that were used to do the fieldwork. At one time I was out in the field for some reason I can’t remember and when it became time for the noon break, Harold put me on top of one of the big horses and told me to ride him to the house. I was petrified! The horses had full harness on because they were not unharnessed until the end of the work day. I hung on for dear life even though the horses were just walking, but when they got nearer to the barn they sensed there was water and hay waiting for them there so they began to run! I don’t believe I have ever been that afraid again since! I began to scream and as we neared the house my sister heard and she ran outside to help me. I wasn’t hurt and was able to be taken off the back of those creatures (they seemed so to me) but my sister sprained her ankle when she jumped off the porch to run to me. <br /><br />

                I also remember at that Roberts farm that Melba and Harold had a cream separator that was used to separate the milk from the cream. That machine was kept on the porch of the house and the cream and milk had to be separated twice a day. The machine had dozens (it seemed that many) of metal disks that the milk ran over which in some magic way actually did separate the cream and milk, but the disks had to be hand washed after each use and of course that was one of my responsibilities…a dreaded one. <br /><br />

                We also became acquainted with fresh grapefruit. Roberts and when Melba brought some home from the store they would cut it in half the night before and cover it with sugar to prepare for eating the next morning. Melba and Harold also lived and worked a farm in Blackfoot, Idaho. The house was a large but old house with buildings where they took care of hogs, cows, a horse or two and chickens. I remember was a pen with huge pigs in it and I was warned carefully “not to go near the pen where the pigs are because if you slipped and fell in the big pig would eat you up!” <br /><br />

                I also had a sad experience where I slept. Melba had fixed up a large closet for me where I might sleep with a cot and a box for bedside table. I was happy to call it my own until I began to notice red welts all over my body and they itched terribly—I complained to my sister and after some investigation into the closet and the bedding it was found that I had been keeping bed bugs company every night! Well, that was a first experience with those creatures. Surely left in the house for our own experience with them…oh, how those bites itched! <br /><br />

                We also had fun in that house. When Bart and I were visiting with Melba and Harold during the Christmas holidays we had a board game we played in the evening when the chores were all finished. It was called “Alley Oop” and why I can still remember the name of the game after all these years…well, probably because board games were very new at that time so we had a real treasure for entertainment. He who won a game would be awarded a “chocolate drop”…a popular treat at that time, and if you bit into the chocolate and found it was pink on the inside then you were rewarded with another! (Oh, the things we do remember!)<br /><br />

                Childhood times on 16th Street still linger in memory. I remember the fun of playing street games with neighborhood friends: “Kick the Can,” “Mother May I,” “Run, Sheep, Run.” We played freely after dark, often under the light of the “ark light” we called them; there was usually an ark light on each comer of a block, high up but providing light for our use. We had little fear of being out after dark, not in those “good old days.” <br /><br />

                Because for many years after we moved to 16th Street the road in front of our house was a graveled road, it was often that those drivers who were going a little too fast past our house often would flip a rock or two which landed into our front room window. Often my dad would react very disgustingly when he had to replace a broken window glass. Joy was the feeling when the more and more roads were paved and ours was one of them! Progress! <br /><br />

                I had one experience with an auto one evening during the winter months when we had lots of good “snowball-making” snow. We kids were out on the boulevard making snowballs and throwing them at cars as they went by when one happened to be a police car and when the policeman driver stopped, of course we kids ran for the dickens. Well, I’m the one who must have not had the speed of the others, for the police followed me home and knocked on the front door with a message for my parents (I was hiding behind my dad), that “your child had not better do that again—or else!” Another memory clincher—never to be forgotten.<br /><br />

                I remember my first date. A friend from the neighborhood lived just down the street, Roy Gardner. He was a good buddy of our next-door neighbor, Don Shearer. We all went to high school together. Don had a model A Ford and he would give us all a ride to school Roy had “eyes” for me, I guess, because he asked me for a date long before my dad would give his permission for me to “go out.” 16 years old…at least…but I remember on my 16th birthday here came Roy for a date to the movies. Roy was a good friend for many years. During the war years when I was in school in Seattle Roy was serving in the Navy and several times he came to visit me at school. He was just a friend to me and I had to eventually tell him that was all our relationship could be. He was a fine and honorable friend, never forgotten.
            </span>

