                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    I have memory of one incident that was quite traumatic to myself and a young friend, Doris Standen, when we interfered with a beehive located somewhere in the area and were both stung by the angry occupants to the extent that Doris was quite ill for a time. I fared much better than she as my injuries from the bees were minor. I also have a memory, however slight, of a big swing in the neighborhood, maybe in the Standen yard or even my yard, that we both enjoyed as kids and friends. <br /><br />

                    The house on Whittier was about a block west of the railroad tracks that run through Idaho Falls. That area was quite sparsely populated in 1926 and there were few houses on the block where we lived. Doris lived just a house or two to the east of us so we were pretty constant play friends. I guess she could be known as the very first friend that I had as a child. When I was about 5 years old my family moved to F street, directly across Memorial Drive from the LDS Hospital. We lived there for about two or three years. <br /><br />

                    The hospital was considered to be quite tall for buildings at that time. It was an impressive building. From the street there was a long walkway up to the front door of the hospital. There could usually be seen at most any time a doctor or a nurse in ter white uniform and cap hurrying up to the door to enter and report for duty. As long as I can remember I have always wanted to be a nurse. I do believe that it was because of the excitement of living near that beautiful hospital.<br /><br />
                    
                    I don’t remember much about the house I believe it was a two story and I’m sure if there was a basement. I remember a garden in the back of tiie house and a barn or shed of some sort. There were a lot of people to live in that house. However, according to my brother, Frant, the older brothers, who would be well into their teens when we moved into that house were off finding work so they could help take care of the large family of brothers and sisters. <br /><br />

                    Rhoe, my oldest brother worked for the Coy Coal company, driving a delivery truck for them. The twin sisters, Melba and Nelda found work at Samsel’s which was a “five and dime” store on A street in Idaho Falls. Frant had left the area and was working in California. Duard (“Dude”) had also left to find work. These were the depression years and it was necessary for those old enough to take work to help the family. They would take on this responsibility either by being out on their own, or else if they lived at home they would help to supplement the income that Dad brought home. <br /><br />

                    My dad worked as a sheep herder, cattle herder or ranch hand and was not home much of the time. I remember when he would come home that I could not remember him, because he would often be away for weeks at a time. None of the older brothers and sisters, excepting Ethel and Bart, and then I, attended high school. <br /><br />

                    I remember one experience at the F street house. My dad was always a very soft hearted person when it came time to punish a child who had misbehaved. That responsibility fell to my mother who usually paddled us when needed. At one time I remember being across her knee being on the receiving end of a spanking and my dad was waiting outside the back door. I could see him there, so that he could comfort me when the ordeal was over. My dad said that those times were about as difficult for him as it was for one being punished. I never remember having him raise a hand to me in any way at anytime. And I remember very few times that my mother punished us that way either. 

