            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText"></span>
                My young days of growing up include several special friends who also lived on 16th Street. One girl friend who lived just three houses from ours was Lois Bacon. She was just a year younger than I and we grew up together and still see each other occasionally. She learned to play the violin very well which I admired a lot and always wished that I could learn to play music of some sort. Our memories of those days in the neighborhood are choice and never to be forgotten. Also close friends through school years were Donna Cook and her sister Marcene. They also lived on 16th Street and we walked to school together and shared a love of movies, especially. <br /><br />

                As young girls were wont to during grade school years my friend, Lois and I played a lot of a game called “Jacks.” It was a favorite game and mostly a girl thing. Lois's father was a photographer (he photographed my wedding) and he captured Lois and I playing Jacks and sent the picture in for consideration at the Chicago World's Fair and…"lo and behold” the photo won honorable mention in its category and was hung in display at the fair (a considerable honor, I might mention…not only for the photographer but for the happy girls)! <br /><br />

                Lois and I spent many years growing up and going to school and church together. Mary Bundte lived across the street from Lois and we also were kind of friends. Donna and Marcene Cook lived on down 16th St towards Boulevard…Lois, Donna, Marcene and I became fast friends through high school years…Three of us…Donna and Marcene and I were enamored with Nelson Eddy and Jeanette MacDonald…musical comedy stars in the movies we went to ALL of their movies. Donna and I collected movie magazines or anything that had pics of them and made scrapbooks; at one time I had three or four huge scrapbooks of them with pictures cut out of the magazines or whatever I could find. (I wonder what my mom did with those scrapbooks when I left to go to college!)  <br /><br />

                I remember a big picture of Nelson Eddy that hung above my bed for years (oh, dear, and nowadays I complain about the teen girls who idolize the rock stars). When a Nelson Eddy movie would come to town, Donna and Marcene and I would go to the matinee when school was out and watch the movie, then go out into the lobby and sit and do our homework while the second feature was playing and then go back in to watch our movie for the second time! Those days we were allowed to stay and watch a movie as many times as we wanted for the price of only one ticket. (Not today!) 
            </span>

