            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText"></span>           

                    About movies then, 1939 or about, I remember vividly when Gone with the Wind came to Idaho Falls. I remember standing in line for tickets and being enthralled that the movie would be in color. Those days folks were shocked at Rhett Butler using the word “damn” in the movie. Not so today…much, much worse. Movies when I was a child and teen were the primary source of entertainment; radio as well. Idaho Falls had four main theaters: Paramount, Rex, Gayety, and Rio. The movies shown would only run for three days and then a new one was shown. <br /><br />

                    Usually there was a news short shown, during the WWII years the main news short was called “Time Marches On.” There was usually a cartoon shown and most often there was a double feature (two main movies), as well as trailers to preview coming attractions. Sunday afternoon was the most popular time to attend the movies, and we always walked about a mile or mile and a half on Saturdays to go. There was always a matinee with a cowboy feature, cartoons and a “serial” movie that would show a continued chapter each Saturday matinee. That would encourage us kids to come every Saturday to see what would happen next to Gene Autry or Roy Rogers, etc.  <br /><br />

                    I remember that the 3rd Ward used to have a movie sponsored in their building on an evening during the week. The one that I remember was a “Fu Man Chu” continued movie. (Oh, my, the things we do remember!) The Rex Theatre on Park Avenue used to have what was called “Country Store Nite” when the owner would turn on the theater lights between the movie double feature and have a drawing where patrons could win sacks of groceries or free popcorn. The owner’s name was Mr. Hager, and I remember he was quite a stem, almost grouchy fellow. We kids were always a little afraid of him; it kept us behaving ourselves at the movies! <br /><br />

                    I remember my first bike, given to me when we lived on 16th Street, as a Christmas gift from my brother Bart and my sister Ethel. I had asked for a bike but hardly believed that I would actually get one. I still remember the feelings I had that Christmas eve while I was trying to sleep, waiting for time to get up in the morning, and sure enough, there was that beautiful bicycle sitting near the tree—what a wonderful Christmas that was. I also remember one Christmas when I was very young that I tried to hide behind the couch to wait for Santa to appear, when my mom or Dad came and said that I might as well go to bed because Santa would never come to a house where the kids were still awake! <br /><br />

                    Well, here’s the TRUE story of how for I walked to high school each day…and home at noon for lunch! Honest…we lived a mile from the high school but not far enough out to get a ride on any school bus, so we walked—winter as well—and home for lunch…which meant taking about 15 minutes to eat and then turn around and walk back to school. Usually there was a friend somewhere along the line to meet and walk with. In my last year, I had a friend who lived next door who had an old car he fixed up and kept running, and often we would get a ride with Don Shearer.  <br /><br />

                    My high school years were spent at the Idaho Falls Senior High School between 6th and 7th Street off the boulevard. I remember the floors in that building being wood and can still often remember the smell of the wood after it had been cleaned and waxed. There was a gymnasium where we were all required to take P.E. (physical education) As it is today there were fads of fashion for clothes that were popular and I remember one particular fad that consisted of a flannel shirt to be worn with a wooden slatted belt that tied in front with leather strips running through the entire belt…extremely high fashion! Also very popular those years were circle skirts and of course for many years…bobby sox! <br /><br />

                    Our school hours were always 9am to 12 noon, then 1pm to 4pm. We had the usually required classes for that time: math, some form of English (English Lit, English history, etc.) physics, P.E. (gym) was required and not an elective; we dressed down into shorts and short sleeved shirt—everybody took gym! We could have an hour of study hall if we chose it. I remember taking chemistry and Latin because it was required pre-requisite in high school for entering a nursing school. My Latin teacher was Mr. Pratt and his classroom was over at the O.E. Bell Junior High School so those who took that class had to trot over to the other building in a hurry to get there on time. (I definitely had a crush on Mr. Pratt, I remember that to be so!)  <br /><br />

                    Ah, those were definitely the “good old school days.” We had hardly any of the problems that students face today.  <br /><br />

                    All I remember about the physics class is this: “a body immersed in a fluid is buoyed up by the force of the fluid it replaces.” (I think of that every time I climb into the bathtub and sit down!)
            </span>

            <!--div id="ChapterPictureGallery" class="clearfix">
                <ol class="GalleryPics">
                        
                </ol>    
            </div-->

            <!--span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                Then when Marlon came home from his mission, I believe we picked him up in Salt Lake. When Robert finished his mission in Australia, we planned to make a major trip down to pick him up. Kenneth and I, and Marlon and Debra left to go down to Australia to pick up Robert. We had a trip that lasted six weeks, and we visited many, many countries in the South Pacific. We visited Mike’s mission and met some of the people that he had worked with in New Zealand. We met many of Robert’s friends and had a very special time there with him. Robert served as an assistant to the president, so he had many things that he could show us in Australia. We thoroughly enjoyed that and met his mission president. 
            </span>
            <span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory4-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory4');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory4" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    From there we went to Indonesia and met many of Marlon’s mission friends as well. They called him “Yellow Bird” down there. We were kind of tickled with that nickname they gave him because of his blond hair. Being there was especially a fun time because we had a very tall Robert, a very rotund Kenneth–he had a little weight on him–and Debra with her long blond hair. That type of person in Indonesia was very, very rare. We attracted a crowd wherever we went. We had people following us and looking at us and wanting to stop and visit. We had a wonderful time. <br /><br />

                    We also went to Taiwan. We went to Thailand. We were in Singapore. We spent time in Japan. We were in Tokyo for three or four days. Then we flew back to Hawaii where Mike and Randy and Janet met us and we spent another week in Hawaii. That was a very special trip and it really gave us the desire to travel as much as we possibly could throughout the following years.  <br /><br />

                    Another special trip we had in our family was when we were going to celebrate our 50th wedding anniversary. Kenneth was just beginning to get into the throes of Alzheimer’s, so we knew that if we wanted to take a family trip together, we must do it at that time. We planned a trip to go to the Mediterranean.  <br /><br />

                    It was kind of interesting how that trip came together, because some of our children just didn’t have the finances to do that trip. They were concerned about it. We wanted to do a family trip for a 50th wedding anniversary, but we didn’t know where we wanted to go or what to do or how long to stay. Finally, Dani called and she said, “Bob is going to put a trip together for us. Let’s go to the Mediterranean. Let’s go take a trip to the Greek Islands.” Oh, my goodness, I thought that would be wonderful. Debra thought it would be wonderful. Bob thought this was wonderful. We began to plan the trip, and pretty soon those who thought they would not go came together, and as a family, all six of our children and their spouses and Ken and I, we made the trip to the Mediterranean.  <br /><br />

                    We went to Rome. We were in Italy for a week or so. We went to the Greek Islands and absolutely fell in love with them. I’ve always wanted to go back to Sorrento in Italy. That was a very special place for me. That was a marvelous trip. The time we spent together as family—we were unbelievably close, helping each other and enjoying the time that we had there. We had some really fun experiences that I would be happy to share with anyone. Anytime they want to listen to me, I’ll tell them of our experiences on that trip.  <br /><br />

                    I’ve been privileged to make several trips to England and travel on the continent with Bob and Janet. They lived there for ten years while Bob was transferred there for his employment. I was privileged to go to England four different times, and it’s become my most favorite place in the world. I love England and I’ll always have special memories. I’m very much connected to England. My ancestors came from there as well, so I guess there’s a spiritual tie there that keeps me in love with England.  <br /><br />

                    It’s interesting, because when Bob and Janet said they’d been transferred to England, I said, “England! Who on earth wants to go and live in England? Are you sure you’re going to do this?” But it just took one trip over there. I went over when Bradley was born. Janet was having some difficulties with that birth, and I went over to help her and just totally fell in love with England.  <br /><br />

                    I’ve been blessed to travel through Europe: Germany, Switzerland, Holland, Italy. I’ve been blessed to travel. I have been blessed to travel! The Lord has been good to me in that respect.  <br /><br />

                    Haven’t been to Alaska. Everyone’s been to Alaska but me.  <br /><br />

                    Oh my goodness, I’ve been to South America. I’ve been to Guatemala. Janet served her mission in Peru and we went down to pick her up and brought her home with us, because we finished our mission in Guatemala as Janet finished hers. We were able to have some of the family go with us, and we went down and picked up Janet and she drove home with us.  <br /><br />

                    Also, when we finished our mission in Guatemala, we brought back with us a fifteen-year-old Guatemalan girl named Norah Alvarado. Her parents were pleased to let her come home with us, and she was able to go to school in Rigby. A couple of years later she came back and attended Ricks College.  <br /><br />

                    I’ve had some beautiful experiences traveling. I’ve had wonderful times and seen a lot of this wonderful world we live in.
                </span>

