            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText"></span>
                    In my teen years I worked for a “five and dime” store named Kress. It was located right next to the Rex Theatre on Park Avenue in Idaho Falls. I worked at the dish counter and that when each counter had its own cash register and each clerk behind each counter was responsible for the money at the end of the shift. I don’t have any bad memories of that job so I must have been able to do a good job. My sister Ethel worked for the store in the office. I also used to do housework for various women around the city and spent many days working full eight or ten hours doing cleaning and receiving the grand sum of $1 when the work was done. <br /><br />

                    During my junior year in high school I got a job working for the Fisher Bakery on A Street in Idaho Falls. I remember when chocolate chip cookies first came on the market and what a big hit they were! Also brownies!<br /><br />
                    
                    Between my junior and senior years at high school I was allowed to take a trip to Seattle on a Greyhound bus to be with my sister Ruby that summer. I spent the entire summer months there working for the 5th Avenue Theater selling popcorn, etc. and showing people down the aisles to their seats…with a flashlight! I loved that summer with Ruby and Jack and Kenny…many memories linger of those days…then, it seemed like summer was much longer than now as an adult. <br /><br />

                    One of the ladies that worked for quite some time and I also babysat for was Una Tate. She was also a registered nurse so she was almost an idol for me to look up to. During the few times when I was working at the LDS hospital as a nurse myself, while on the medical floor as the night charge nurse, I learned that Una Tate was a patient. She was a heart patient and was in critical condition and not expected to live through the night. She ended up surviving, but I did not see or hear from her for many years. <br /><br />

                    Then in the January of 1979, Grant Tate, her husband, appeared at our door at the farm, demonstrating some special vitamins that he was representing. He asked if he could bring his wife in, and to my great surprise it was Mrs. Tate! We had an enjoyable few minutes together, reliving some memories. Even though her condition prevented her from speaking, the love and friendship we felt for each other was still evident after many years.
            </span>

            <!--div id="ChapterPictureGallery" class="clearfix">
                <ol class="GalleryPics">
                        
                </ol>    
            </div-->

            <!--span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                The home was on seven acres. There are two acres of woods, two acres of pastures, and then an acre and a half for the home. I’m not sure just what the numbers are.<br /><br />

                After we had lived here for a number of years, we found that the family loved to come here. They often planned their summer vacations to come, and eventually we had family reunions. I'm not sure just which year we started; I think it was about 1989. The family loved to come especially for reunions. We managed to put everyone up, and they loved to be together. They looked forward to coming and we looked forward so much to having them come. To be together, to show the love we feel for each other, and to see the cooperation—it was just full of love! The reunions have been wonderful. 
            </span>
            <span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory5-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory5');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory5" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    We always had a theme for our reunions, and everyone in the family participated. We had committees. Everyone was part of a committee, preparing meals and preparing games to play. The food was a big deal. We always tried to have special food that everyone would enjoy. We often had the food catered, but mostly family wanted to work together, to be together, and to have fun together. Our family has always had those blessings of enjoying being together and looking forward to reunion time. We had about half a dozen reunions here in this home. <br /><br />

                    I think reunions are a very special part of family relationships. They bring families together; for those who’ve lived far away and been separated for a number of years, when they come to a reunion—I don't know how to describe it. It's such a warm, special time to be together with those that you love and be part of a very special family. We have always enjoyed having the reunions.<br /><br />

                    The last one we had here had about eighty-five people. It was a riot! A riot. Everyone loved it. We had barrels of fun. We were together for about four days total. Some even wanted to stay longer. Family from Mesa traveled so far and they wanted to come and stay longer, so of course we welcomed that. It's a special feeling to know that your family wants to come back home and to be with you—very special.<br /><br />

                    Cyndi gave me a kitchen towel, and the last reunion she hung it on my oven door and I didn't know who left it there. But the towel explains a family. I believe the towel says, “Home is where Mom is.” That's kind of what family is. We don't have a dad right now, but home is where Mom and Dad are, wherever they live. That's where home is. <br /><br />

                    We've always been a close family. We've always enjoyed being close together. We've had many, many blessings in our family because of our love of the gospel, our desire to be together, and the love we feel for one another.
                </span>

