            We had one dog while I was in junior and senior high school. He was there still when I came home from Seattle and college. “Old Sox” was his name and so named because he had 4 white sox on his feet. He lived to be 17 years old and was my dad’s most favorite pet of all. We had several pets at the farm, some cats and some dogs. I remember the big white Tom that we called Tomboy who didn’t come inside too often because he was just a little too wild, also a big yellow cat that we called “George Cat” when we lived in Rexburg. We also had a favorite dog named “Little Joe” from the farm. <br /><br />

            Much later in life, one October during the school break for potato harvest, Janet and Debra and I went on a three day trip to Salt Lake to just have fun and we happened to pass by a pet shop while we were wandering around shopping, etc. and there we found “Sam Dog,” a Beagle puppy. He was just a baby and we were so smitten with him that we just had to buy him and take him home. I think he cost $20 or so, if my memory is right. He was such a darling little puppy. We even smuggled him into our hotel room safely! We had Sam for many years. The whole family loved Sam Dog. He quickly became part of us and we loved him for many years. <br /><br />

            We also had “George Cat,” who became part of our family for a number of years and we loved him as well. We also had for just a few months a beautiful cat that we agreed to take for Mary Gibson’s son who could no longer keep him as he was moving back east. This cat was named “Spock.” l am sure after the famous Dr. Spock of Star Trek, the famous TV program for years! Spock was never comfortable with us because he was a one man pet so we eventually took him to the farm and gave him to Darrell and Mary Hersley, my nephew and niece who were renting the farmhouse at that time. They told us later that Spock didn’t like them either and he eventually ran away from home.

            </span>

            <!--div id="ChapterPictureGallery" class="clearfix">
                <ol class="GalleryPics">
                                      
                </ol>    
            </div-->

            <!--span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">

                    I would wish for them to have the kind of family that I have had. I would like to see them have families where their children grow up in the gospel and have strong, viable testimonies of the gospel as my children have had and as my husband and I have had. I would wish for them a tremendous posterity, as I have had. Heavenly Father has blessed me tremendously with my family. I couldn’t have asked to have a better family than I’ve had. My posterity, as well, is just…I can’t describe how pleased and happy and blessed I feel to have my family. 
 
            </span-->
            
            <!--span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory6-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory6');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
